limerick_list.text:
It's a snake's poisoned fang (do not tickle!);
A sword (saves your skin in a pickle);
In your brain, it's a fold;
But a wrestling hold?
No, for falx always means 'like a sickle'.

About termites, three things I'll confide:
Some reside in cut lumber that's dried;
Some are alate, thereby,
With small wings they can fly;
And those alates taste nutty when fried.

Yeah, your wife's the best cook on the street;
All her dishes are subtle and sweet.
But her cover charge sucks;
She wants thirty-one bucks
Just to let you sit down in a seat.

Soundproof walls to stop noise from each yell;
Charcoal filters to cut sulfur's smell;
Wind- and sun-powered fires;
Emission-free pyres;
TV and free wifi as well.

When resentful, my mentor's a venter;
He raises his voice like a stentor;
So my heart's really beating
As we go to this meeting
Where I'll speak at the conference center.

The telly and horses are set,
As I light up a charcoal briquette.
There's shrimp on the barbie;
I'm watching the derby;
Much better my life couldn't get.

I accorded the lady my arm;
She accorded her smile and her charm.
  I accorded my hand
  Her prohibited land;
She accorded significant harm.

He had dotted the i's, crossed the t's;
Second-guessed their intentions with ease;
Made the running, but what's
Better still—called the shots;
Came in first; ran the show; earned his fees.

Biorhythmic, I measure my days:
Twenty-three in the physical ways;
My emotional peak
Hits me every fourth week;
Thirty-three and my mind will amaze.

If you follow your heart and your dreams
To the Lake District's mountains and streams;
If you venture on high,
Keep an eye on the sky;
You're in Cumbria — land of extremes!

Don't worry—relax—don't be scared.
First, a rhyme (call it A) fits line one;
It's all right if you feel unprepared.
Then line two (also A) has its fun.
Things are different this time;
A new rhyme for line three
For convenience, this rhyme
And line four (call it B);
Has been captioned, for limerick-impaired.
Back to A for line five, and we're done.

Yellow's five; three's light green; red is two;
Purple's four; white is one; nine is blue;
Eight is brown; seven's black;
Dark green's six. Got the knack?
Orange ten. Count again. This I knew.

Hey, besmearer! You stain, you pollute;
Ruination's your evil pursuit.
Not a tear do you shed
For the dirt that you spread;
You do not (horrid brute!) give a hoot.

"Just look at this beast, Anne," said teacher;
"Do you see that abdominal feature?
What does it resemble, Anne?
That's right: a collembolan;
It can spring — oops, it's gone! (Curse the creature!)"

He's a deviator, that is for sure,
Crossing lines, keeping limits obscure.
Raised a Jew, he eats pork;
Slurps his soup with a fork;
Wears a parka in Kuala Lumpur...

To cultivate (verb): farm or grow;
To encourage; to culture; to sow;
To foster; promote;
Nourish; rear; keep afloat.
Said of plants, or a friend, or a foe.
